cal colleges in Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1982]]\n[[Category:1982 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name                   = M.M.U.College of Pharmacy\n| image                  = M.M.U.College_of_Pharmacy_Logo.jpg\n| established            = {{Start date and age|1982}}\n| city                   = [[Ramanagara]]\n| academic_affiliation   = [[Rajiv Gandhi University of Health Sciences|RGUHS]] <br/> [[All India Council for Technical Education|AICTE]] <br/>[[Pharmacy Council of India|PCI]]\n| founder:               = Syed Muneer\n| principal              = Dr. Mohammed Khaleel\n| state                  = [[Karnataka]]\n| country                = [[India]]\n| postalcode             = 562159\n| campus                 = [[Urban area|Urban]]\n| website                = {{URL|www.mmupharmacy.org}}\n}}\n\n[[M.M.U.College of Pharmacy]], an institution run by Madras-E-Madinathul-Uloom Trust (M.M.U.Trust) is situated in between the beautiful mountains about 50 km from Bangalore on Bangalore-Mysore highway in the silk city of Ramanagaram.<ref>http://www.mmupharmacy.org/</ref>\n\n== History ==\nM.M.U.College of Pharmacy was established in the year 1982 with the [[Diploma in Pharmacy]]. In the year 1982 they started [[Bachelor of Pharmacy]], Post graduate courses in pharmacy ([[Master of Pharmacy|M. Pharm]]) started from 2009.<ref>http://www.mmupharmacy.org/</ref>\n\n== Academic ==\nM.M.U.College of Pharmacy offering several programs of study in the field of pharmacy,such as 2 years Master in Pharmacy (M. Pharm), 4 years Bachelor in Pharmacy (B. Pharm) and 2 years Diploma in Pharmacy (D. Pharm).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://collegedunia.com/college/56632-m-m-u-college-of-pharmacy-ramanagar|title=M. M. U. College of Pharmacy, Ramanagar|website=Collegedunia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n[[Category:Pharmacy schools in India]]\n[[Category:Colleges in Bangalore]]\n[[Category:Colleges affiliated to Rajiv Gandhi University of Health Sciences]]\n[[Category:Medical colleges in Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1982]]\n[[Category:1982 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Friendsamin", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M.M.U.College_of_Pharmacy"}
{"title_page": "React Native", "text_new": "{{short description|open-source mobile application framework created by Facebook}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=February 2019}}{{Infobox software\n| name = React Native\n| logo = React-icon.svg\n| developer = Facebook and community\n| released = {{Start date and age|2015|03|26}}<ref name=\"initialrelease\">{{cite web |title=React Native: Bringing modern web techniques to mobile |url=https://code.fb.com/android/react-native-bringing-modern-web-techniques-to-mobile/}}</ref>\n| latest release version = 0.62.0\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|03|26}}<ref name=\"ghrelease\">{{cite web |url=https://github.com/facebook/react-native/releases |title=Releases \u2013 Facebook/React |website=[[GitHub]]}}</ref><!-- DO NOT CHANGE THIS REFERENCE: the GitHub release page can remain as a static reference for all foreseeable releases-->\n| repo = https://github.com/facebook/react-native\n| programming language = [[JavaScript]], [[Java (programming language)|Java]], [[C++]], [[Objective-C]], [[Objective-C++]], [[Python (programming language)|Python]]\n| platform = \n| license = [[MIT License]]\n| website = {{URL|https://reactnative.dev/}}\n}}\n\n'''React Native''' is an [[Open-source software|open-source]] [[Application framework|mobile application framework]] created by [[Facebook]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://facebook.github.io/react-native/|title=React Native \u00b7 A framework for building native apps using React|accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref> It is used to develop applications for [[Android (operating system)|Android]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://code.facebook.com/posts/1189117404435352/react-native-for-android-how-we-built-the-first-cross-platform-react-native-app/|title=Android Release for React Native}}</ref>, [[iOS]], [[Website|Web]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/necolas/react-native-web/|title=React Native for Web|accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref> and [[Universal Windows Platform|UWP]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.windows.com/buildingapps/2016/04/13/react-native-on-the-universal-windows-platform/|title=React Native on the Universal Windows Platform|author=Windows Apps Team|date=April 13, 2016|website=blogs.windows.com|accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref> by enabling developers to use [[React (JavaScript library)|React]] along with native platform capabilities.\n\nAn incomplete port for [[Qt (software)|Qt]] also exists.<ref>https://github.com/status-im/react-native-desktop</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn 2012 [[Mark Zuckerberg]] commented, \"The biggest mistake we made as a company was betting too much on HTML as opposed to native\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Zuckerberg's Biggest Mistake? 'Betting on HTML5'|url=https://mashable.com/2012/09/11/html5-biggest-mistake|publisher=Mashable|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> He promised that [[Facebook]] would soon deliver a better mobile experience.\n\nInside [[Facebook]], Jordan Walke found a way to generate [[User_interface|UI]] elements for iOS from a background [[JavaScript]] [[Thread_(computing)|thread]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/React_(JavaScript_library)|title=React (JavaScript library)}}</ref> They decided to organise an internal [[Hackathon]] to perfect this [[prototype]] in order to be able to build [[Mobile_app|native apps]] with this technology.<ref>{{cite web|title=A short Story about React Native|url=https://jobninja.com/blog/short-story-react-native/|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter months of development, [[Facebook]] released the first version for the React JavaScript Configuration in 2015. During a technical talk,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Christopher|first1=Chedeau|title=A Deep Dive into React Native|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7rDsRXj9-cU|website=YouTube|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> Christopher Chedeau explained that [[Facebook]] was already using React Native in production for their Group App and their Ads Manager App.<ref name=\"initial_rn_post\">{{cite web|url=https://code.facebook.com/posts/1014532261909640/react-native-bringing-modern-web-techniques-to-mobile/|title=React Native: Bringing modern web techniques to mobile|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Implementation==\n\nThe working principles of React Native are virtually identical to [[React (JavaScript library)|React]] except that React Native does not manipulate the [[Document_Object_Model|DOM]] via the [[React_(JavaScript_library)#Virtual_DOM|Virtual DOM]]. It runs in a [[background process]] (which interprets the [[JavaScript]] written by the developers) directly on the end-device and communicates with the native platform via a [[serialization|serialisation]], [[Asynchrony_(computer_programming)|asynchronous]] and [[Batch_processing| batched]] Bridge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bridging in React Native|url=https://tadeuzagallo.com/blog/react-native-bridge/|accessdate=16 January 2018|date=14 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://parsed.io/react-native-vs-flutter/| title=React Native vs Flutter: Which Cross-Platform Framework is Better?|accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://blog.uptech.team/how-we-build-apps-on-react-native-part-2-7-things-you-should-know-to-save-your-development-time-944533f81c03|title=How we build React Native app: 7 things which save your development time. Part 2|accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\nReact components wrap existing native code and interact with native APIs via React\u2019s [[Declarative programming|declarative UI paradigm]] and [[JavaScript]]. This enables native app development for whole new teams of developers, and can let existing native teams work much faster.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.xongolab.com/blog/how-react-native-can-empower-your-mobile-app-development-process/| title=How React Native can Empower App Development Process?|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nReact Native does not use [[HTML]] or [[CSS]]. Instead, messages from the JavaScript thread are used to manipulate native views. React Native also allows developers to write native code in languages such as [[Java_(programming_language)|Java]] for [[Android_(operating_system)|Android]] and [[Objective-C]] or [[Swift_(programming_language)|Swift]] for [[iOS]] which make it even more flexible.\n\n==Hello World Example==\n\nA [[\"Hello,_World!\"_program| Hello, World]] program in React Native looks like this:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"js\" line=\"1\">\nimport React from 'react';\nimport { AppRegistry, Text } from 'react-native';\n\nconst HelloWorldApp = () => <Text>Hello world!</Text>;\nexport default HelloWorldApp;\n\n// Skip this line if using Create React Native App\nAppRegistry.registerComponent('HelloWorld', () => HelloWorldApp);\n\n// The React native code can also be imported from another component with the following code:\nimport HelloWorldApp from './HelloWorldApp';\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n[[Category:Mobile software development]]\n[[Category:Software using the MIT license]]\n[[Category:Facebook software]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|open-source mobile application framework created by Facebook}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=February 2019}}{{Infobox software\n| name = React Native\n| logo = React-icon.svg\n| developer = Facebook and community\n| released = {{Start date and age|2015|03|26}}<ref name=\"initialrelease\">{{cite web |title=React Native: Bringing modern web techniques to mobile |url=https://code.fb.com/android/react-native-bringing-modern-web-techniques-to-mobile/}}</ref>\n| latest release version = 0.62.0\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|03|26}}<ref name=\"ghrelease\">{{cite web |url=https://github.com/facebook/react-native/releases |title=Releases \u2013 Facebook/React |website=[[GitHub]]}}</ref><!-- DO NOT CHANGE THIS REFERENCE: the GitHub release page can remain as a static reference for all foreseeable releases-->\n| repo = https://github.com/facebook/react-native\n| programming language = [[JavaScript]], [[Java (programming language)|Java]], [[C++]], [[Objective-C]], [[Objective-C++]], [[Python (programming language)|Python]]\n| platform = \n| license = [[MIT License]]\n| website = {{URL|https://reactnative.dev/}}\n}}\n\n'''React Native''' is an [[Open-source software|open-source]] [[Application framework|mobile application framework]] created by [[Facebook]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://facebook.github.io/react-native/|title=React Native \u00b7 A framework for building native apps using React|accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref> It is used to develop applications for [[Android (operating system)|Android]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://code.facebook.com/posts/1189117404435352/react-native-for-android-how-we-built-the-first-cross-platform-react-native-app/|title=Android Release for React Native}}</ref>, [[iOS]], [[Website|Web]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://github.com/necolas/react-native-web/|title=React Native for Web|accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref> and [[Universal Windows Platform|UWP]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.windows.com/buildingapps/2016/04/13/react-native-on-the-universal-windows-platform/|title=React Native on the Universal Windows Platform|author=Windows Apps Team|date=April 13, 2016|website=blogs.windows.com|accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref> by enabling developers to use [[React (JavaScript library)|React]] along with native platform capabilities.\n\nAn incomplete port for [[Qt (software)|Qt]] also exists.<ref>https://github.com/status-im/react-native-desktop</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nIn 2012 [[Mark Zuckerberg]] commented, \"The biggest mistake we made as a company was betting too much on HTML as opposed to native\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Zuckerberg's Biggest Mistake? 'Betting on HTML5'|url=https://mashable.com/2012/09/11/html5-biggest-mistake|publisher=Mashable|accessdate=7 April 2018}}</ref> He promised that [[Facebook]] would soon deliver a better mobile experience.\n\nInside [[Facebook]], Jordan Walke found a way to generate [[User_interface|UI]] elements for iOS from a background [[JavaScript]] [[Thread_(computing)|thread]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/React_(JavaScript_library)|title=React (JavaScript library)}}</ref> They decided to organise an internal [[Hackathon]] to perfect this [[prototype]] in order to be able to build [[Mobile_app|native apps]] with this technology.<ref>{{cite web|title=A short Story about React Native|url=https://jobninja.com/blog/short-story-react-native/|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter months of development, [[Facebook]] released the first version for the React JavaScript Configuration in 2015. During a technical talk,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Christopher|first1=Chedeau|title=A Deep Dive into React Native|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7rDsRXj9-cU|website=YouTube|accessdate=16 January 2018}}</ref> Christopher Chedeau explained that [[Facebook]] was already using React Native in production for their Group App and their Ads Manager App.<ref name=\"initial_rn_post\">{{cite web|url=https://code.facebook.com/posts/1014532261909640/react-native-bringing-modern-web-techniques-to-mobile/|title=React Native: Bringing modern web techniques to mobile|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Implementation==\n\nThe working principles of React Native are virtually identical to [[React (JavaScript library)|React]] except that React Native does not manipulate the [[Document_Object_Model|DOM]] via the [[React_(JavaScript_library)#Virtual_DOM|Virtual DOM]]. It runs in a [[background process]] (which interprets the [[JavaScript]] written by the developers) directly on the end-device and communicates with the native platform via a [[serialization|serialisation]], [[Asynchrony_(computer_programming)|asynchronous]] and [[Batch_processing| batched]] Bridge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bridging in React Native|url=https://tadeuzagallo.com/blog/react-native-bridge/|accessdate=16 January 2018|date=14 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= https://parsed.io/react-native-vs-flutter/| title=React Native vs Flutter: Which Cross-Platform Framework is Better?|accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://blog.uptech.team/how-we-build-apps-on-react-native-part-2-7-things-you-should-know-to-save-your-development-time-944533f81c03|title=How we build React Native app: 7 things which save your development time. Part 2|accessdate=2019-11-06}}</ref>\n\nReact components wrap existing native code and interact with native APIs via React\u2019s [[Declarative programming|declarative UI paradigm]] and [[JavaScript]]. This enables native app development for whole new teams of developers, and can let existing native teams work much faster.{{Citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\nReact Native does not use [[HTML]] or [[CSS]]. Instead, messages from the JavaScript thread are used to manipulate native views. React Native also allows developers to write native code in languages such as [[Java_(programming_language)|Java]] for [[Android_(operating_system)|Android]] and [[Objective-C]] or [[Swift_(programming_language)|Swift]] for [[iOS]] which make it even more flexible.\n\n==Hello World Example==\n\nA [[\"Hello,_World!\"_program| Hello, World]] program in React Native looks like this:\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=\"js\" line=\"1\">\nimport React from 'react';\nimport { AppRegistry, Text } from 'react-native';\n\nconst HelloWorldApp = () => <Text>Hello world!</Text>;\nexport default HelloWorldApp;\n\n// Skip this line if using Create React Native App\nAppRegistry.registerComponent('HelloWorld', () => HelloWorldApp);\n\n// The React native code can also be imported from another component with the following code:\nimport HelloWorldApp from './HelloWorldApp';\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Facebook navbox}}\n[[Category:Mobile software development]]\n[[Category:Software using the MIT license]]\n[[Category:Facebook software]]\n", "name_user": "Himanshumstry", "label": "safe", "comment": "I just added relative link at the place of citation needed.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/React_Native"}
{"title_page": "Locator map", "text_new": "Hello |Simple map used in cartography to show the location of a particular geographic area within its larger and presumably more familiar context;can be used on its own or as an inset or addition to a larger map}}\nA '''locator map''', sometimes referred to simply as a ''locator'', is typically a simple [[map]] used in [[cartography]] to show the location of a particular [[geography|geographic area]] within its larger and presumably more familiar context. Depending on the needs of the cartographer, this type of map can be used on its own or as an inset or addition to a larger map.\n\n==Purpose==\n[[Arthur H. Robinson|Arthur Robinson]], an American cartographer influential in [[thematic map|thematic cartography]], stated that a map not properly designed \"will be a cartographic failure.\"<ref>{{cite book | author=Robinson, A.H. | title=Elements of Cartography | location=New York | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | year=1953}}</ref> Any map that does not take its audience into account by assuming too much reader knowledge about the map area's context will not fulfill its purpose. Location maps help achieve this purpose by familiarizing the reader with the location of an area they may not have read about previously. A good understanding of the audience's [[mental mapping|mental map]] for a particular area is critical for a proper application of location maps. \nUsed on their own, location maps do not differ significantly from traditional maps, differing primarily in the fact that solitary locator maps focus the attention on a single location within the map frame, where traditional maps generally seek to portray a multitude of features across the entire frame.\nMore commonly, location maps appear as insets or ancillary maps (maps adjacent to or near the primary map) in order to help the audience place the geographic area being mapped properly inside their internal frame of reference.\n\n==Common uses==\n\n===Education===\n[[Image:Location Algeria.svg|thumb|Example of a world location map for Algeria.]]\nAs [[Education|educators]] seek to teach students increasing levels of geography, maps generated for textbooks must reference the expected geographic knowledge of a particular education level. Location maps achieve this purpose by highlighting more in-depth geography within the context the student is familiar with. \nIn the United States, this purpose is reinforced by the standards set by the National Council for Geographic Education, which says that \"Mental maps, or cognitive maps, are among our most important geographic tools. Because they exist in our minds, they are the maps we use for thinking and decision-making.\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ncge.org/standards/ \n |title=National Geography Standards \n |accessdate=2008-06-24 \n |author=National Council for Geographic Education \n |year=1994 \n |work=Geography Education Standards Project \n |publisher=National Geographic Society Committee on Research and Exploration \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209041349/http://www.ncge.org/standards/ \n |archivedate=2008-02-09 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\n===Interactive applications===\nSome online applications that allow the user to zoom into an area often include locator maps to assist in navigating the main map or image. For example, [[Google Maps]] uses a locator map to orient visitors to its site, included as a toggle button. These locators often feature a movable box that assists the user with navigating the main map.\nOther applications using [[locator software]] allow people to generate their own location maps by entering some basic information about where they are. This generates a map showing places within a specified radius of that point that meet the user's criteria. Banks, hotels, retail chains, and restaurants are common users of this type of service.\n\n===Commerce===\n[[File:SVG locator map.svg|thumb|right|Simplified locator map displaying places of interest]]\nBusinesses have a vested interest in letting [[consumer]]s know where they are located, and frequently use locator maps to help them reach out to potential customers. These maps typically range from a crude schematic map showing nearby crossroads, to more realistic maps that include greater geographic detail and context.\n\n====Corporate web sites====\nBusinesses such as [[restaurant]]s and [[retailing|retail establishments]] often have locator maps online to help potential customers find their location. These are sometimes accompanied by driving and parking directions from one or more directions of travel, especially if many of their customers are not from the local area.\n\n====Direct marketing====\n[[Image:generic locator LG.png|thumb|Sample locator map showing the location of a hotel by a highway interchange.]]\nThe widespread distribution of sophisticated [[Geographic Information System]] (GIS) mapping techniques has allowed the development of large-scale customized locator maps that can be tailored to individual consumers in [[direct marketing]] campaigns. This sophistication allows a variety of customized locator maps to be produced in a relatively short period of time.\nMajor types of direct marketing locator maps are:\n\n*'''Single Location''': A single business location is shown with major street and road connections. While this type of map can be efficiently constructed using GIS with existing street databases and customized map templates, special software is not required because the map does not change for each direct mailing.\n*'''Customer to Business''': Using a customer address list, specialized software can frame the map that shows a customer's location in relation to the business, and connects the two using a pre-existing street database.\n*'''Multiple Location''': Like the single location locator map, a GIS package is not required, though it also can be useful in quickly plotting the locations onto an existing street database using map templates.\n*'''Defined Area Locators''':<ref>{{cite book | author=Lockmore, Alexander Robert Ulysses | title=Annual Register Vol. 21  | location=London | year=1778}}</ref> Multiple locations within a defined area are shown.\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Locator maps}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Map types]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Simple map used in cartography to show the location of a particular geographic area within its larger and presumably more familiar context;can be used on its own or as an inset or addition to a larger map}}\nA '''locator map''', sometimes referred to simply as a ''locator'', is typically a simple [[map]] used in [[cartography]] to show the location of a particular [[geography|geographic area]] within its larger and presumably more familiar context. Depending on the needs of the cartographer, this type of map can be used on its own or as an inset or addition to a larger map.\n\n==Purpose==\n[[Arthur H. Robinson|Arthur Robinson]], an American cartographer influential in [[thematic map|thematic cartography]], stated that a map not properly designed \"will be a cartographic failure.\"<ref>{{cite book | author=Robinson, A.H. | title=Elements of Cartography | location=New York | publisher=John Wiley & Sons | year=1953}}</ref> Any map that does not take its audience into account by assuming too much reader knowledge about the map area's context will not fulfill its purpose. Location maps help achieve this purpose by familiarizing the reader with the location of an area they may not have read about previously. A good understanding of the audience's [[mental mapping|mental map]] for a particular area is critical for a proper application of location maps. \nUsed on their own, location maps do not differ significantly from traditional maps, differing primarily in the fact that solitary locator maps focus the attention on a single location within the map frame, where traditional maps generally seek to portray a multitude of features across the entire frame.\nMore commonly, location maps appear as insets or ancillary maps (maps adjacent to or near the primary map) in order to help the audience place the geographic area being mapped properly inside their internal frame of reference.\n\n==Common uses==\n\n===Education===\n[[Image:Location Algeria.svg|thumb|Example of a world location map for Algeria.]]\nAs [[Education|educators]] seek to teach students increasing levels of geography, maps generated for textbooks must reference the expected geographic knowledge of a particular education level. Location maps achieve this purpose by highlighting more in-depth geography within the context the student is familiar with. \nIn the United States, this purpose is reinforced by the standards set by the National Council for Geographic Education, which says that \"Mental maps, or cognitive maps, are among our most important geographic tools. Because they exist in our minds, they are the maps we use for thinking and decision-making.\"<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.ncge.org/standards/ \n |title=National Geography Standards \n |accessdate=2008-06-24 \n |author=National Council for Geographic Education \n |year=1994 \n |work=Geography Education Standards Project \n |publisher=National Geographic Society Committee on Research and Exploration \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080209041349/http://www.ncge.org/standards/ \n |archivedate=2008-02-09 \n |url-status=dead \n}}</ref>\n\n===Interactive applications===\nSome online applications that allow the user to zoom into an area often include locator maps to assist in navigating the main map or image. For example, [[Google Maps]] uses a locator map to orient visitors to its site, included as a toggle button. These locators often feature a movable box that assists the user with navigating the main map.\nOther applications using [[locator software]] allow people to generate their own location maps by entering some basic information about where they are. This generates a map showing places within a specified radius of that point that meet the user's criteria. Banks, hotels, retail chains, and restaurants are common users of this type of service.\n\n===Commerce===\n[[File:SVG locator map.svg|thumb|right|Simplified locator map displaying places of interest]]\nBusinesses have a vested interest in letting [[consumer]]s know where they are located, and frequently use locator maps to help them reach out to potential customers. These maps typically range from a crude schematic map showing nearby crossroads, to more realistic maps that include greater geographic detail and context.\n\n====Corporate web sites====\nBusinesses such as [[restaurant]]s and [[retailing|retail establishments]] often have locator maps online to help potential customers find their location. These are sometimes accompanied by driving and parking directions from one or more directions of travel, especially if many of their customers are not from the local area.\n\n====Direct marketing====\n[[Image:generic locator LG.png|thumb|Sample locator map showing the location of a hotel by a highway interchange.]]\nThe widespread distribution of sophisticated [[Geographic Information System]] (GIS) mapping techniques has allowed the development of large-scale customized locator maps that can be tailored to individual consumers in [[direct marketing]] campaigns. This sophistication allows a variety of customized locator maps to be produced in a relatively short period of time.\nMajor types of direct marketing locator maps are:\n\n*'''Single Location''': A single business location is shown with major street and road connections. While this type of map can be efficiently constructed using GIS with existing street databases and customized map templates, special software is not required because the map does not change for each direct mailing.\n*'''Customer to Business''': Using a customer address list, specialized software can frame the map that shows a customer's location in relation to the business, and connects the two using a pre-existing street database.\n*'''Multiple Location''': Like the single location locator map, a GIS package is not required, though it also can be useful in quickly plotting the locations onto an existing street database using map templates.\n*'''Defined Area Locators''':<ref>{{cite book | author=Lockmore, Alexander Robert Ulysses | title=Annual Register Vol. 21  | location=London | year=1778}}</ref> Multiple locations within a defined area are shown.\n\n==References==\n{{Commons category|Locator maps}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Map types]]\n", "name_user": "81.97.33.119", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Locator_map"}
